edgenote624 = ccc.edgenotes.build
edgenote624.caption = 'As chairman of the Adaptation Steering Committee, Kidane has to be knowledgeable about the international climate framework. So do you.'
edgenote624.format = :aside
edgenote624.thumbnail_url = 'http://remley.wcbn.org/ihih-msc/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/UNFCCC1009.jpg'
edgenote624.content = '<h3>UNFCCC and National Adaptation Programmes of Action (NAPA)</h3>
<p>The United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) is an international environmental agreement working towards the stabilization of greenhouse gas concentrations in the atmosphere at levels that will prevent anthropogenic interference with the climate system. The UNFCCC is currently the only international climate policy venue with broad legitimacy. As part of the Marrakech Accord of 2001, member states agreed to the creation of National Adaptation Programmes of Action (NAPAs), as part of a new approach to addressing urgent adaptation needs in Least Developed Countries (LDCs). By focusing on vulnerability from the long-term state policy level, the NAPA approach is designed to value community-level input and recognize communities as stakeholders in the identification and implementation of adaptation strategies. NAPAs support adaptation efforts in LDCs because of these countries’ limited abilities to create and fund policies to mitigate negative climate impacts.</p>
<p>NAPAs provide a process to assist LDCs in identifying priority adaptation projects. The emphasis on addressing urgent and immediate needs helps the UNFCCC and countries select projects which would cost more to complete once climate change damage is sustained. Because NAPAs are intended to be used and understood by policy-level decision-makers and the general public, no further research into the projects is required. Within the report, each LDC is responsible for providing a list of projects and project profiles ranked by priority.</p>
'
edgenote624.slug = 'napa'
edgenote624.save

